    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-12-03T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-12-03T22:00:00-05:00" n="639"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d639">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">693.003/528: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chairman of the American Delegation</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Arnold</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-12-04T11:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 4, 1918, 11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[<hi rend="italic">Received December 4, 6.33 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Is American delegate correct in assuming that American acquiescence in present
                    maritime tariff revision is dependent upon proportionate increases in frontier
                    tariffs? American trade will suffer in competition with Japanese land borne
                    trade if frontier tariffs not proportionately increased.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Arnold</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
